comment.editorialComment: As we approach the end of the year we would expect the market to toughen and with this will come reduced footfall at dealer level and less activity from buyers in the wholesale arena. This sector is often one of the first to react to this kind of pressure and it isn’t unusual to see values moving by as much as -3% as we go through the month.

The market in December can be very mixed, particularly in this sector. While there will still be some business around, trade buyers become very cautious and very rarely put a positive spin on things. This means that although they will still be out buying, there is an expectation that things will be much cheaper during the short time that vendors have to move their stock in December. The outcome of this has meant that we have now become used to seeing a market movement of around -3.0% during the course of the month.

`Historically, January is always expected to be a strong month in terms of values. This is usually driven by renewed enthusiasm from both trade and retail buyers following the extended Christmas break. This sector in particular, is usually one of the first to react to the market. This is usually driven by plenty of choice across all ages and also many dealers will offer strong incentives to the consumer during January. On the back of this, values are likely to remain fairly stable as we go through the month and the market begins to gain momentum again.
